node.text:
originally, I wanted to caption this with “bitch don’t I look like a pharaoh?” (because, hello?) & leave it at that. but because I am a woman & because I have this particular body that is constantly being policed, a photo like this—where I am taking up space with my body regally, where I am celebrating my sensuality—is (begrudgingly) a political statement.
i’ve known that Instagram hates women for a while now, what with their censorship of women’s bodies (& bodily functions), nipples, & their sexuality. i’ve experienced this hatred personally (many of my non-explicit photos of my body have been removed for being “pornographic” & “unsafe”) & also as an empathetic witness—several of my women/femme friends + colleagues have been banned from this platform for life because of posting things mentioned above. this hatred & aversion of women is common knowledge at this point. but it’s recently gone to other more dangerous levels.
did you know that Instagram is currently (like, as we speak) blocking hashtags like #woman #femalestripper & any tags having to do with SW rights? I’m also getting reports that #boobs & #bra are being blocked for some people, too. this is all thanks to that fosta/sesta bill that was passed recently. & this is more than just sex-negativity. this is misogyny. this is censorship. this is violence.
if you believe in the bodily autonomy + the sexual agency & liberation of ALL people—including SWs—please please please use your platform to speak up about this. especially if you do work in this realm of sexual liberation—that includes you tantric teachers & healers, sex + relationship coaches, yoni egg peddlers, & people who do “pole fitness”. if you’re not angry, you should be.
& fuck you Instagram for making me have to talk about your fucking woman-hating nonsense when all I wanted to do was post this bomb photo of me looking like a goddamn magical Empress incarnate. & fuck you doubly for making me censor out my perfect nipples which takes away from the beauty of this photo. may you feel the heat of my wrath & utter discontentment until you do better.
➖

@mara.dower there is a lot to unpack here that I don’t have time to do, but you asked “where do you draw the line?” & my first thought is that maybe 12 is a bit too young to be on Instagram? that’s personally where I would draw the line. not just for questionable content (which, let’s be real—she’s likely seeing questionable content in other places if she has a smartphone with access to the internet) but also because places like Instagram can be harmful to people’s—particularly young girls—psychological development. studies have shown this. so i personally would draw the line by not having my daughter on this platform until she’s a bit older. & if not that, then maybe having a conversation with your daughter about the difference between porn & women’s bodies being celebrated (because I know you know the difference) is in order. or just a conversation about the male gaze. or that adult women get to choose what to do with & how to show off their bodies—even pornographers—because they have agency & they are human beings who deserve to be respected. IDK. like I said, lots to unpack here, & by that I mean you have a lot to unpack—with yourself & with your daughter.
@evyan.whitney yes it’s all def tricky in this day and age - one that is moving so rapidly and me as a parent trying to navigate. Thanks for your reply. 🙏

I just came across you through @julesyparker and scrolling through your feed. I came across this and you look beautiful. I totally hear your comment but my question is where do you draw the line? My daughter is 12, has been on Instagram for a year and has access to the full plethora of what’s on insta feeds. Also my account got hacked by a porn site which I have to say the images were horrendous. So where does the line get drawn? How do young teenage girls differentiate, understand, accept the beautiful-ness of our bodies when it’s depicted in so many ways? Like I said I have literally come across you and I’ll listen to Julies’s podcast. But I am interested in what you feel about this and how mothers/parents navigate devices, insta feeds that sometimes do have pornographic content in them, and hashtags that don’t always reflect the empress side of a woman’s body that young children who have devices can type in to see it all. ❤️

Thank you for reposting this on your story today. I woke up feeling ashamed in my own skin postpartum, and with all the practices I have I still couldn’t get to this feeling of royalty that i was able to hold just a few months ago before my birth injury. I separated my pubic bone and have felt like it scattered my roots and root stuff everywhere. As I pick up the pieces, seeing so much of my consciousness live in my pussy, some days I struggle to be the empress again. So I appreciate this mirror. I also appreciate what you have done to speak truth to this, the banning and censoring of female empowerment, while the male gaze photo with the patriarchal poise harms as destroys. How this is all so related to sex work, the liberation of the very thing that is our total fucking essence! Sexuality. Sexual healing. Sexual embodiment. It’s all threatening to the system because this is the power that will break it down. Thank you for mirroring embodiment and truth today, I needed it as do millions of others. Thank you for your work. Xo 👑✨👑

And also thank you for showing up and saying that all sexuality work is on a spectrum of sex work. The sexological Bodyworker, the dancer, the escort, the pole dance class, the priestess schools, the sex therapists and new sex Ed, the sexual healer, the sex magic witch, the writers, the sluts, yoni eggs, crystal Healing, the cam workers, the woman out there knowing her gift is in sexuality, however it shows up. The idea that this is a spectrum is potent and recognized and I hear you exclaim the truth in this way. That you don’t get to teach pole class and not show up politically to support sex workers. That this divide is built on racism and classism and heteronormative capitalist ideals. I also hear you saying once again it’s okay and good to love the fuck out of your body and yourself. Thank you. Xo
